{"title_page": "Pendro", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Pendro\n|native_name            = {{lang-ku|P\u00eandro ,\u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6}}\n|other_name             = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = Pendroo-jalalmajid1968.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Pendro and [[Mount Butin]] (1968)\n|pushpin_map            = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|37|03|42|N|44|06|20|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Province]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[Subdistricts of Iraq|Subdistrict]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Mergasor District|Mergasor]]\n|subdivision_name4      = '''Shirwan Mezin'''\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|leader_title           = [[Mukhtar]]\n|leader_name            = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = 1325\n|elevation_ft           =\n|population_total       = 2,547\n|population_as_of       = 2017\n|population_footnotes   =\n|population_density_km2 =\n| population_demonym    = '''''Pendroi'''''\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n|area_code              = 0750\n|timezone               = [[UTC+03:00|UTC+3]]  \n|utc_offset             = \n}}\n\n'''Pendro''' or '''Pendru''' ({{lang-ku|\u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6, P\u00eandro}})<ref>{{cite news |title=Balafir\u00ean Tirkiyey\u00ea \u00eari\u015f\u00ee kamp\u00ean PKK\u00ea kirin |url=https://rudaw.net/kurmanci/kurdistan/230920155 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=R\u00fbdaw |date=23 September 2015 |language=ku}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u06af\u0627\u0644\u06d5\u0631\u06cc - \u06a9\u0648\u06ce\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6 |url=https://www.rudaw.net/sorani/yourrudaw-08062014051033 |publisher=R\u00fbdaw |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=ku}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n village in [[Kurdistan Region]], located in [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil Province]], close to the border with [[Turkey]], it is located approximately 15\u201318&nbsp;km to the north from [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]], of population over 2540 people and located in central [[Muzuri Kurds|Muzuri Bala]] one of the seven tribes of [[Barzani Kurds|Barzan]]. It lies in a valley surrounded by low peaks and mount [[Mount Butin|Butin]] about 4 km northeast of Pendro and also the canyon of [[Sardav Canyon|Sardav]] is about fifteen minutes walk from the north end of the village. The villages of Banan and Shive to the north, [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]] to the northeast, Edlbey and Zet to the east, Selke, Stope and Guiza Walati to the south, Binavye and Navkorka to the west, Dezo and Spindare to the northwest. The area of Pendro covers over {{convert|10|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}. The terrain is highly mountainous, lying within the [[Zagros]]; less than 10% of the Pendro is below {{convert|1225|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}, and its highest point is {{convert|2534|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}. All population speaks local [[Bahdini]] dialects of [[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] as their native language, and [[Central Kurdish]] in its standard form is the [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]]'s official language.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n\n== History ==\n\nPendro's history stretches back to at least the era of [[Bahdinan|Badinan Emirate]] rule in [[Amadiya]], which ended conclusively in 1843.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ceylan|first1=Ebubekir|title=Ottoman Origins of Modern Iraq: Political Reform, Modernization and Development in the Nineteenth Century Middle East|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85772-041-2|pages=50, 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EFwBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51|language=en}}</ref> Pendro is inhabited by the [[Muzuri Kurds|Muzuri]] clan for hundreds of years. Muzuri is one of the oldest [[Kurds|Kurdish]] tribes in [[Iraqi kurdistan|Kurdistan]]. The [[Muzuri Kurds|tribe]] first time mentioned by [[Sharafkhan Bidlisi]] in his book [[Sharafnama]] in 1597.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bidl\u012bs\u012b|first1=Sharaf Kh\u0101n|last2=Izady|first2=Mehrdad R.|title=The Sharafnam\u0302a, or, The history of the Kurdish nation, 1597|publisher=Mazda|isbn=978-1-56859-074-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U50sAQAAIAAJ|year=2005}}</ref> Muzuri tribe mentioned by [[Evliya \u00c7elebi]] in his [[Travel literature|travelogue]] called the ''[[Seyahatname]]'' (\"Book of Travel\") in 1638,<ref>{{cite book|last1=\u00c7elebi|first1=Evliya|title=The Intimate Life of an Ottoman Statesman, Melek Ahmed Pasha (1588\u20131662): As Portrayed in Evliya Celebi's Book of Travels (Seyahat-name)|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-0640-3|page=175|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YiWSuO6fdQYC&pg=PA175|year=1991}}</ref> and mentioned by [[Mark Sykes]] in 1909, Also mentioned by the Kurdish historian [[Muhammad Amin Zaki|Zaki]] in his book (Kurd and Kurdistan) in 1931.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bayg|first1=Muhammad Amin Zaki|title=Zubah-i Tarikh-i Kurd va Kurdistan|publisher=Intisharat-i Tus|isbn=9789643155650|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLEkSAAACAAJ|year=2002}}</ref> The terrain, wooded and mountainous, favored the Kurdish-[[Kurdish nationalism|nationalists]] and [[Social movement]]. Throughout history, the region had been invaded many times by external powers. Pendro and other villages in region were enemy's biggest geopolitical threat. Many times the villagers were forced to leave and destroyed their villages, Kurdish enemy did this because too many villagers had rebelled and were fighting for [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] independence.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Xebat Newspaper|journal=Xebat.net|url=http://xebat.net/1/detail_articals.php?id=34013&z=11&l=1|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728080054/http://xebat.net/1/detail_articals.php?id=34013&z=11&l=1|archive-date=2017-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Many Pendroi joined the first [[Ahmed Barzani revolt|Barzan Revolt]] which ended in 1932 and Shaykh [[Ahmed Barzani]] was later forced to flee to [[Turkey]] with 400 [[Barzani Kurds|Barzani]] families, this number includes 31 Pendroi families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofkurd.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B2-1.pdf|title=The first of the major Barzani revolts|newspaper=historyofkurd.com|date=2016|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728074611/http://www.historyofkurd.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B2-1.pdf|archive-date=2017-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> One decade later in 1943 [[Mustafa Barzani]] was escape from his exile in [[Sulaymaniyah]], he returned to [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]] and he had visited a number of villages in the region and a number of village men soon joined him and captured and disarmed the local police. A bloody clash between the [[Mustafa Barzani|Barzani]] and [[Military intelligence]] officers in Pendro, this clash that led to the death of the three [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraqi]] Military intelligence officers, that was the beginning of [[1943 Barzani revolt]]. Occupation of Barzan on 7 October 1945 by [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]], forced [[Mustafa Barzani|Barzani]] to order his forces to retreat from the region and cross into [[Iranian Kurdistan]] with nearly three thousands Barzani, 165 of them came from Pendro. And later settled and join establishing the [[Republic of Mahabad]]. After [[Mahabad Republic]] was overrun by Iran's army, Barzani and his 500 followers took refuge in [[Soviet]], including 19 Pendroi.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barzani|first1=Massoud|title=Mustafa Barzani and the Kurdish Liberation Movement|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-29316-1|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yx7UqM31KYUC&pg=PA65|date=2003}}</ref> Over 150 Pendroi participated in [[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War|Aylul Revolution]] and Gulan Revolution. After [[1975 Algiers Agreement|Algiers Accord]] over sixty thousands Kurdish, including 116 Pendroy families forced to become refugees, fleeing mostly to neighbouring Iran. On 25 June 1978 Iraqi Army removed all villagers nearer the border to different camps in [[Erbil Province]] and destroyed the villages, all Pendroi settled in Bahirka camp, the region entirely destroyed and left uninhabitable.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHAT HAPPENED IN THE KURDISH GENOCIDE|url=http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&pnr=37|website=uk.gov.krd|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080615/http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&pnr=37|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> Genocide against the Barzani Kurds by Iraqi regime in 1983, the killing of the 8,000 Barzani, 16 victims were from Pendro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drmohammedihsan.com/Images/Service/FROM%20BLUEPRINT%20TO%20GENOCIDE.pdf|title=FROM BLUEPRINT TO GENOCIDE?|newspaper=drmohammedihsan.com|date=2014|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109061446/http://drmohammedihsan.com/Images/Service/FROM%20BLUEPRINT%20TO%20GENOCIDE.pdf|archive-date=2017-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Agency, krg.org |title=Iraqi tribunal rules Barzani killings in 1983 were genocide |url=https://ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2011/5/state5086.htm |website=ekurd.net |access-date=2018-09-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810143427/https://ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2011/5/state5086.htm |archive-date=2018-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Various waves of Kurdish genocide|url=http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&smap=170000&pnr=48|website=uk.gov.krd|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901063048/http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&smap=170000&pnr=48|archive-date=2017-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[Kurdish rebellion of 1983|Kurdish Rebellion]] some Pendroi families went back to Pendro and rebuilt new village in the north, toward to the mount [[Mount Butin|Butin]] an area of the land called \"Mlane\", once again their village destroyed by Iraqi regime in 1987 and villagers forced to become refugees in Iran.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pendro Etymology|url=http://ekurds.com/kurdish/pendro.htm|work=ekurds|access-date=2017-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417155614/http://www.ekurds.com/kurdish/pendro.htm|archive-date=2017-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1991, after [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|Kurdish Uprisings]], people came back to the village and it was rebuilt in 1994 by one of the [[United Kingdom|British]] organizations. The new village rebuilt about {{convert|1.5|km|mi|0}} west of Pendro a region of the land called \"Chema\". But two years later the village destroyed during the [[Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict (1978\u2013present)|PKK-Turkish]] conflict.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nawzad Hluri |title=\u0632\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u0647\u200c\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u06c6\u0631\u062f\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0634\u0647\u200c\u0648\u06cc \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0648\u06cc \u0641\u0695\u06c6\u0643\u0647\u200c \u062a\u0648\u0631\u0643\u06cc\u06cc\u0647\u200c\u0643\u0627\u0646 |url=http://wishe.net/dreja.aspx?=hewal&jmare=22855&Jor=1 |work=wishe |access-date=2017-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810112121/http://wishe.net/dreja.aspx?=hewal&jmare=22855&Jor=1 |archive-date=2018-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:KurdistanMountainClimbing.jpg|Kurdistan Mountain Climbing Federation Heading to the Sardav Canyon (2015)|thumb|left]]\nPendro lies at an altitude of {{convert|1325|m|ft|0}} [[above mean sea level|above sea level]] and covers an area over {{convert|10.0|km2|sqmi|1}}. It is located in northern [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]]. The terrain mostly consists of mountains and [[hill]]s, with very little moderately sloping [[plain]]s. The lowest point is the '''Chema''' [[Stream]], at 1174 metres, and the highest is [[Mount Butin]], at 2,534 metres, in the Chema, just west of the confluence of the many [[Stream]]. Mountain ranges in the proximity of the village are [[Mount Butin|Butin]] and '''Kerye Spindare''', more to the south are '''Misek''' and '''Kore Hure'''. Pendro has neither rivers nor lakes. In terms of land boundaries, Pendro borders Edlbey, Zet, Banan, Shive, Dezo, Spindare, Navkorka, Binavye, Stope, Selke, Guiza Walati and [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]] for over {{convert|50|km|mi|0}}. The nearest major towns are '''Sherwan Mezin''', {{convert|14|km|mi|0}} away to the south-east, [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]], {{convert|18|km|mi|0}} away to the south and capital [[Erbil]], {{convert|172|km|mi|0}} to the south (by road). The village-wide common lands called: ''Sebaski'', ''Gure'', ''Chema'', ''Mlane'', ''[[Mount Butin|Butine]]'', ''Elye'', ''leri'' and ''Ser xingel''. Pendro has so many [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]]s the main springs are ''Kanya Gundi'', ''Kanya Serderave'', '' Kani Jefre'', ''Kanya Mlane'', ''Kanya Butine'', ''Kanya Helara'' and ''Kanya Mira''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Bordering villages ===\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Pendro\n|North     = '''Shive''', '''Banan'''\n|Northeast = [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]]\n|East      = '''Edlbey''', '''Zet'''\n|Southeast = \n|South     = '''Guiza Walati''', '''Selke''', '''Stope'''\n|Southwest = \n|West      = '''Navkorka''', '''Binavye'''\n|Northwest = '''Spindare''', '''Dezo'''\n}}\n\n==Climate==\nPendro's clamate is [[Hot-summer humid continental climate|Hot/warm-summer humid continental]] (''[[humid continental climate|Dsa]]'') according to [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Weather in region is moderate especially in winter which is very cold and rainy (more than {{convert|1500|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} in some years) in addition to the fall of {{convert|150|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} of snow annually. January is the wettest month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weather in Pendro, Arbil|url=https://us.worldweatheronline.com/pendro-weather/arbil/iq.aspx|website=us.worldweatheronline.com}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box |metric first= Yes |single line= Yes |location= Pendro (2009\u20132016)\n|Jan record high C= 13.0\n|Feb record high C= 17.0\n|Mar record high C= 20.0\n|Apr record high C= 27.0\n|May record high C= 33.0\n|Jun record high C= 39.0\n|Jul record high C= 44.0\n|Aug record high C= 44.0\n|Sep record high C= 40.0\n|Oct record high C= 31.0\n|Nov record high C= 22.0\n|Dec record high C= 14.0\n|Jan high C= 9.5\n|Feb high C= 12.2\n|Mar high C= 16.2\n|Apr high C= 23.0\n|May high C= 29.6\n|Jun high C= 36.7\n|Jul high C= 41.0\n|Aug high C= 40.7\n|Sep high C= 35.2\n|Oct high C= 27.5\n|Nov high C= 18.8\n|Dec high C= 12.2\n|Jan mean C = 6.1\n|Feb mean C = 8.5\n|Mar mean C = 11.7\n|Apr mean C = 18.0\n|May mean C = 25.6\n|Jun mean C = 31.7\n|Jul mean C = 35.3\n|Aug mean C = 34.7\n|Sep mean C = 29.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.3\n|Nov mean C = 14.6\n|Dec mean C = 7.1\n|Jan low C= 1.8\n|Feb low C= 3.2\n|Mar low C= 5.0\n|Apr low C= 9.5\n|May low C= 15.6\n|Jun low C= 21.2\n|Jul low C= 23.6\n|Aug low C= 22.2\n|Sep low C= 17.3\n|Oct low C= 13.5\n|Nov low C= 7.6\n|Dec low C= 3.5\n|Jan record low C= -9.0\n|Feb record low C= -12.0\n|Mar record low C= -2\n|Apr record low C= 10.0\n|May record low C= 14\n|Jun record low C= 20.0\n|Jul record low C= 22.0\n|Aug record low C= 20.0\n|Sep record low C= 14.0\n|Oct record low C= 9.0\n|Nov record low C= -1.0\n|Dec record low C= -5.0\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm=155.1\n|Feb rain mm=91.0\n|Mar rain mm=143.6\n|Apr rain mm=89.1\n|May rain mm=51.0\n|Jun rain mm=2.9\n|Jul rain mm=1.5\n|Aug rain mm=1.3\n|Sep rain mm=3.9\n|Oct rain mm=53.9\n|Nov rain mm=85.0\n|Dec rain mm=141.6\n|snow colour = green\n|Jan snow cm = 12.0\n|Feb snow cm = 34.3\n|Mar snow cm = 16.9\n|Apr snow cm = 1.0\n|May snow cm = 0.0\n|Jun snow cm = 0.0\n|Jul snow cm = 0.0\n|Aug snow cm = 0.0\n|Sep snow cm = 0.0\n|Oct snow cm = 0.0\n|Nov snow cm = 0.0\n|Dec snow cm = 7.2\n|Jan rain days=12.3\n|Feb rain days=10.5\n|Mar rain days=14.8\n|Apr rain days=12.5\n|May rain days=10.7\n|Jun rain days=3.7\n|Jul rain days=0.5\n|Aug rain days=1.5\n|Sep rain days=2.3\n|Oct rain days=8.5\n|Nov rain days=9.8\n|Dec rain days=11.1\n|Jan snow days=2.2\n|Feb snow days=3.6\n|Mar snow days=5.5\n|Apr snow days=0.9\n|May snow days=0.0\n|Jun snow days=0.0\n|Jul snow days=0.0\n|Aug snow days=0.0\n|Sep snow days=0.0\n|Oct snow days=0.0\n|Nov snow days=0.0\n|Dec snow days=1.7\n|Jan humidity=64.8\n|Feb humidity=60.8\n|Mar humidity=58.8\n|Apr humidity=51.5\n|May humidity=37.3\n|Jun humidity=22.8\n|Jul humidity=18.6\n|Aug humidity=18.7\n|Sep humidity=24.7\n|Oct humidity=36.8\n|Nov humidity=47.8\n|Dec humidity=59.2\n|source 1= Worldweatheronline [https://us.worldweatheronline.com/pendro-weather-averages/arbil/iq.aspx]\n|source 2= Accuweather [http://www.accuweather.com/en/iq/pendro/503090/weather-forecast/503090]\n|date=April 2014}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n===People===\nPendro is the 3rd-largest village in [[Muzuri Kurds|Muzuri]] tribe by population, in the 2017 Census conducted by '''Muhammadali Sa\u2018id''' Pendroi,<ref>{{cite web|title=Muhamadali Sayid ,2017 Census|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=1283699921667021&set=a.186742458029445.34902.100000810761354&type=3&theater|website=www.facebook.com|language=en}}</ref> the Village of Pendro recorded a population of 2547, the census revealed the following numbers: 1290 females (50.65%), 1257 males (49.35%). More than half of them living in Bahirka since 1978.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em; float:left;\"\n|+Pendroi in [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]] (2017)\n|-\n! Rank\n! Place\n! Households\n|-\n!1\n| Bahirka\n|342\n|-\n!2\n|[[Erbil]]\n|67\n|-\n!3\n|Pirmam\n|59\n|-\n!4\n|[[Soran, Iraq|Soran]]\n|46\n|-\n!5\n|[[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]]\n|18\n|-\n!6\n|[[Dohuk]]\n|16\n|-\n!7\n|Rezan\n|11\n|-\n!8\n|Ble\n|9\n|-\n!9\n|Syrye\n|5\n|-\n!10\n|[[Zakho]]\n|1\n|-\n!11\n|Selke\n|1\n|-\n!12\n|Gureto\n|1\n|-\n!13\n|Shaneder\n|1\n|-\n!14\n|Shakholan\n|1\n|-\n!'''Total'''\n|'''14'''\n|'''578'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:96%;\"  \n|+Pendroi [[Diaspora]] (2017)\n\n! Rank\n! Country\n! Households\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |1\n| [[United States]]\n|10\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |2\n| [[Germany]]\n|8\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |3\n| [[Sweden]]\n| 7\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |4\n| [[Russia]]\n| 5\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |5\n| [[Denmark]]\n| 5\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |6\n| [[Netherlands]]\n| 4\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |7\n| [[UK]]\n| 3\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |8\n| [[Canada]]\n| 2\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |9\n| [[Australia]]\n| 1\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''45'''\n|}\n\n===Education===\n\n[[File:Jalal Majid Amin 1968.jpg|thumb|Pendro [[Elementary School]] students and teachers (1968)]]\nAccording to a 2017 census by '''Muhammadali Sa\u2018id''' Pendroi,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pendro village|url=https://www.facebook.com/PENDROVillage/photos/pb.137995939723983.-2207520000.1494309405./598298140360425/?type=3&theater|website=www.facebook.com|language=en}}</ref> Pendro is one of the most educated villages in the [[Mergasor District]]. With over 50 percent of Pendroi adults having attained at least an undergraduate college or university degree.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em; float:left;\"\n|+Pendroi students in all Educational stage\n|-\n! Rank\n! Stage\n! Male\n! Female\n! Total\n|-\n!1\n| First Grade to Twelfth Grade\n| 343\n| 310\n| 653\n|-\n!2\n| University\n| 49\n| 52\n| 101\n|-\n!3\n| Educational Institutions\n| 16\n| 17\n| 33\n|-\n!4\n| Doctoral\n| 4\n| 1\n| 5\n|-\n!5\n| Master\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n|-\n! '''Total'''\n| '''5'''\n| '''423'''\n| '''371'''\n| '''794'''\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:96%;\"  \n|+ Educational Attainment of the Pendroi\n! Rank\n! Degree & Diploma\n! Male\n! Female\n! Total\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |1\n| University\n| 131\n| 98\n| 229\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |2\n| Institution\n| 65\n| 77\n| 142\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |3\n| Master\n| 14\n| 4\n| 18\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |4\n| Doctoral\n| 4\n| 2\n| 6\n|-\n!style=\"text-align: right;\" |5\n| High Diploma\n| 2\n| 0\n| 2\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''5'''\n| '''216'''\n| '''181'''\n| '''397'''\n|}\n\n==Wildlife==\nEnvironmental protection in Pendro and other parts of [[Barzani Kurds|Barzani]] tribes  began during the leadership of [[Ahmed Barzani|Khudan]], he has banned the cutting of trees and hunting wild animals, especially [[wild goat]] and more progressive environmental protection had it start in the 1990s.\n\n===Flora===\n[[File:17092007Pendro.Sleman,Leyl,Surme,Bengin&Saleh.jpg|thumb|After [[harvest]] the villagers removing [[almond]] hulls, Pendro (2007)]]\nPendro has a hundreds species of plants,<ref name=\"kurdflora\">{{cite web|title=Home {{!}} Kurd Flora|url=http://www.kurdflora.com|website=www.kurdflora.com|access-date=2018-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928044312/http://www.kurdflora.com/|archive-date=2018-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref> some of species are introduced and non-native. More than 70% the area of the Pendro is forested, with stands of [[Platanus orientalis|Plane tree]], [[Oak]], [[Quercus infectoria]], [[Chestnut]], [[Pistacia atlantica]], [[Almond]], [[Walnut]], [[Common fig|Fig]], [[Vitis]], [[Pear]], [[Morus nigra]], [[Apricot]], [[Plum]], [[Apple]], [[Pomegranate]], [[Peach]], [[Quince]], [[Sumac]] and other valuable trees. Mountain herbs such as [[Agaricus|Mushroom]], [[Ferulago]], [[Fennel]], [[Allium ampeloprasum|Wild leek]], [[Carduus nutans]], [[Arum]], [[Allium haemanthoides|Allium]], [[Rheum ribes]] and many other mountain herbs. In flowers include [[Narcissus \u00d7 medioluteus|Narcissus]], [[Fritillaria imperialis]], [[Papaver rhoeas]] and other beautiful flowers.<ref name=\"mushroom\">{{cite web|title=Survey and Identification of Mushrooms in Erbil Governorate (PDF Download Available)|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261551919|website=ResearchGate|language=en|access-date=2017-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928044017/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261551919_Survey_and_Identification_of_Mushrooms_in_Erbil_Governorate|archive-date=2018-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Fauna===\n\n==== Mammals ====\nAnimals that inhabit around the Pendro include [[Brown bear]], [[Syrian brown bear]], [[Persian squirrel|Squirrel]], [[Wild goat]], [[Boar]], [[Gray wolf|Wolf]], [[Striped hyena|Hyena]], [[Golden jackal]], [[Mouflon]], [[European badger|Badger]], [[Crested porcupine]], [[Marbled polecat]], [[Red Fox|Fox]], [[European hare|Hare]], [[Long-eared hedgehog|Hedgehog]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farhadinia|first1=Mohammad Sadegh|last2=Valizadegan|first2=Negin|title=A preliminary baseline status of the Syrian Brown Bear Ursus arctos syriacus (Mammalia: Carnivora: Ursidae) in Golestanak, Northern Iran|url=http://www.threatenedtaxa.in/index.php/JoTT/article/view/1787/3104|website=Journal of Threatened Taxa|pages=6796\u20136799|language=en|date=26 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814161724/http://www.threatenedtaxa.in/index.php/JoTT/article/view/1787/3104|archivedate=14 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NMNH Department of Systematic Biology, Division of Mammals - Mammal Species of the World Home Page|url=http://nmnhgoph.si.edu/msw/|date=27 April 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427043030/http://nmnhgoph.si.edu/msw/|archivedate=27 April 2007}}</ref> '''Felidae''' in this family include [[Wild cat]], [[Caracal]].\n\n==== Birds ====\nTens of thousands birds from many species pass through Pendro and surrounding villages during the bi-annual migration season, from [[Caucasus]] and West Asia to south Iraq and south-east Iran in the winter, and back in the spring. Entire region is the stopover point for thousands birds migrating from Caucasus to [[Persian gulf|Gulf]] and migrating [[Common crane|Crane]]s some time take a pause because of bad weather as they travel between breeding and wintering grounds. These are some names of bird species in Pendro and surrounding areas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iraq bird checklist|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/checklist.jsp?lang=EN&region=iq&list=clements|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2017-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922085253/http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/checklist.jsp?lang=EN&region=iq&list=clements|archive-date=2012-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Chukar partridge|Chukar]], [[See-see partridge|Partridge]], [[Black francolin|Francolin]], [[Common quail|Quail]], [[Common crane|Crane]], [[Black kite]], [[Griffon vulture|Vulture]], [[Short-toed snake eagle|Eagle]], [[Western marsh harrier|Harrier]], [[Common buzzard]], [[Long-legged buzzard|Buzzard]], [[Greater spotted eagle|Eagle]], [[Golden eagle]], [[Common kestrel|Kestrel]], [[Peregrine falcon|Falcon]], [[Great egret|Egret]], [[Squacco heron|Heron]], [[White stork|Stork]], [[Eurasian teal|Teal]], [[Mallard]], [[Eurasian stone-curlew|Curlew]], [[Common tern|Tern]], [[Rock pigeon]], [[Stock dove|Dove]], [[Common wood pigeon|Pigeon]], [[Common cuckoo|Cuckoo]], [[Barn owl|Owl]], [[Eurasian eagle-owl|Eagle-owl]], [[Brown fish owl]], [[Little owl]], [[European nightjar|Nightjar]], [[Alpine swift]], [[Common swift|Swift]], [[Kingfisher]], [[European bee-eater]], [[Blue-cheeked bee-eater|Bee-Eater]], [[Hoopoe]], [[Syrian woodpecker]], [[European green woodpecker|Woodpecker]], ( eight species of [[Lark]]), [[Eurasian wren|Wren]], [[Alpine accentor|Accentor]], [[Common blackbird|Blackbird]], [[Mistle thrush|Thrush]], [[Song thrush]], ( over four species of [[Warbler]]), [[European robin]], [[Rufous-tailed scrub robin|Robin]], [[White-throated robin]], [[Eurasian blue tit|Blue tit]], [[Great tit]], [[Sombre tit|Tit]], [[Common redstart|Redstart]], [[Rock nuthatch]], [[Persian nuthatch]], [[Woodchat shrike|Shrike]], [[Masked shrike]], [[Eurasian jay]], [[Eurasian magpie|Magpie]], [[Common raven|Raven]], [[Hooded crow|Crow]], [[Common starling|Starling]], [[Yellowhammer]], [[Pine bunting|Pine]], ( at least over six species of [[Bunting (bird)|Bunting]] bird), [[Common chaffinch|Chaffinch]], [[Brambling]], [[European goldfinch|Goldfinch]], [[Twite]], [[European serin|Serin]], [[House sparrow|Sparrow]], there are over 30 species of [[Old World sparrow|Sparrow]] worldwide and eight species which occur in areas.\n\n==== Reptiles and Others ====\nThe following are some of the reptiles of  Pendro, primarily covering the region in northeast [[Iraqi kurdistan|Kurdistan]]. [[Macrovipera lebetina obtusa|Macrovipera]], [[Dolichophis jugularis|Dolichophis]]. [[Montivipera raddei|Kurdistan viper]], [[Testudo (genus)|Testudo]], [[Spur-thighed tortoise|Spur]], [[Ophisops]], [[Carinatogecko|Gecko]], [[Mediterranean house gecko|House gecko]], some other species of [[Snake]], [[lizard]] and [[Turtle]] occur in region. '''Amphibians''' in this [[Class (biology)|class]], [[Pelobates syriacus|Frog]], [[Marsh frog]] and other amphibians. Pendro has thousands of '''Invertebrates''' and '''Invasive species'''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Venomous Snakes In Iraq|url=http://www.reptilesmagazine.com/Snakes/Wild-Snakes/Venomous-Snakes-In-Iraq/|website=www.reptilesmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522015018/http://www.reptilesmagazine.com/Snakes/Wild-Snakes/Venomous-Snakes-In-Iraq/|archive-date=2017-05-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Iraq Check List|url=https://www.inaturalist.org/check_lists/8811-Iraq-Check-List?page=2|website=iNaturalist.org|access-date=2018-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030205849/https://www.inaturalist.org/check_lists/8811-Iraq-Check-List?page=2|archive-date=2018-10-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pendro}}\n* [https://pendrovillage.webs.com/ Pendro Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140717073135/http://hawlergov.org/ku/region.php?id=1330759021 Erbil Governorate]\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Erbil Governorate]]\n[[Category:Geography of Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n[[Category:Villages in Arbil Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Pendro\n|native_name            = {{lang-ku|P\u00eandro ,\u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6}}\n|other_name             = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = Pendroo-jalalmajid1968.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Pendro and [[Mount Butin]] (1968)\n|pushpin_map            = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|37|03|42|N|44|06|20|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Province]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[Subdistricts of Iraq|Subdistrict]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Mergasor District|Mergasor]]\n|subdivision_name4      = '''Shirwan Mezin'''\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|leader_title           = [[Mukhtar]]\n|leader_name            = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = 1325\n|elevation_ft           =\n|population_total       = 2,547\n|population_as_of       = 2017\n|population_footnotes   =\n|population_density_km2 =\n| population_demonym    = '''''Pendroi'''''\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n|area_code              = 0750\n|timezone               = [[UTC+03:00|UTC+3]]  \n|utc_offset             = \n}}\n\n'''Pendro''' or '''Pendru''' ({{lang-ku|\u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6, P\u00eandro}})<ref>{{cite news |title=Balafir\u00ean Tirkiyey\u00ea \u00eari\u015f\u00ee kamp\u00ean PKK\u00ea kirin |url=https://rudaw.net/kurmanci/kurdistan/230920155 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=R\u00fbdaw |date=23 September 2015 |language=ku}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u06af\u0627\u0644\u06d5\u0631\u06cc - \u06a9\u0648\u06ce\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u06ce\u0646\u062f\u0631\u06c6 |url=https://www.rudaw.net/sorani/yourrudaw-08062014051033 |publisher=R\u00fbdaw |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=ku}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]] village in [[Kurdistan Region]], located in [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil Province]], close to the border with [[Turkey]], it is located approximately 15\u201318&nbsp;km to the north from [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]], of population over 2540 people and located in central [[Muzuri Kurds|Muzuri Bala]] one of the seven tribes of [[Barzani Kurds|Barzan]]. It lies in a valley surrounded by low peaks and mount [[Mount Butin|Butin]] about 4 km northeast of Pendro and also the canyon of [[Sardav Canyon|Sardav]] is about fifteen minutes walk from the north end of the village. The villages of Banan and Shive to the north, [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]] to the northeast, Edlbey and Zet to the east, Selke, Stope and Guiza Walati to the south, Binavye and Navkorka to the west, Dezo and Spindare to the northwest. The area of Pendro covers over {{convert|10|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}. The terrain is highly mountainous, lying within the [[Zagros]]; less than 10% of the Pendro is below {{convert|1225|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}, and its highest point is {{convert|2534|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}. All population speaks local [[Bahdini]] dialects of [[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] as their native language, and [[Central Kurdish]] in its standard form is the [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]]'s official language.\n\n== History ==\n\nPendro's history stretches back to at least the era of [[Bahdinan|Badinan Emirate]] rule in [[Amadiya]], which ended conclusively in 1843.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ceylan|first1=Ebubekir|title=Ottoman Origins of Modern Iraq: Political Reform, Modernization and Development in the Nineteenth Century Middle East|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85772-041-2|pages=50, 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EFwBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51|language=en}}</ref> Pendro is inhabited by the [[Muzuri Kurds|Muzuri]] clan for hundreds of years. Muzuri is one of the oldest [[Kurds|Kurdish]] tribes in [[Iraqi kurdistan|Kurdistan]]. The [[Muzuri Kurds|tribe]] first time mentioned by [[Sharafkhan Bidlisi]] in his book [[Sharafnama]] in 1597.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bidl\u012bs\u012b|first1=Sharaf Kh\u0101n|last2=Izady|first2=Mehrdad R.|title=The Sharafnam\u0302a, or, The history of the Kurdish nation, 1597|publisher=Mazda|isbn=978-1-56859-074-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U50sAQAAIAAJ|year=2005}}</ref> Muzuri tribe mentioned by [[Evliya \u00c7elebi]] in his [[Travel literature|travelogue]] called the ''[[Seyahatname]]'' (\"Book of Travel\") in 1638,<ref>{{cite book|last1=\u00c7elebi|first1=Evliya|title=The Intimate Life of an Ottoman Statesman, Melek Ahmed Pasha (1588\u20131662): As Portrayed in Evliya Celebi's Book of Travels (Seyahat-name)|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-0640-3|page=175|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YiWSuO6fdQYC&pg=PA175|year=1991}}</ref> and mentioned by [[Mark Sykes]] in 1909, Also mentioned by the Kurdish historian [[Muhammad Amin Zaki|Zaki]] in his book (Kurd and Kurdistan) in 1931.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bayg|first1=Muhammad Amin Zaki|title=Zubah-i Tarikh-i Kurd va Kurdistan|publisher=Intisharat-i Tus|isbn=9789643155650|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLEkSAAACAAJ|year=2002}}</ref> The terrain, wooded and mountainous, favored the Kurdish-[[Kurdish nationalism|nationalists]] and [[Social movement]]. Throughout history, the region had been invaded many times by external powers. Pendro and other villages in region were enemy's biggest geopolitical threat. Many times the villagers were forced to leave and destroyed their villages, Kurdish enemy did this because too many villagers had rebelled and were fighting for [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] independence.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Xebat Newspaper|journal=Xebat.net|url=http://xebat.net/1/detail_articals.php?id=34013&z=11&l=1|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728080054/http://xebat.net/1/detail_articals.php?id=34013&z=11&l=1|archive-date=2017-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Many Pendroi joined the first [[Ahmed Barzani revolt|Barzan Revolt]] which ended in 1932 and Shaykh [[Ahmed Barzani]] was later forced to flee to [[Turkey]] with 400 [[Barzani Kurds|Barzani]] families, this number includes 31 Pendroi families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofkurd.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B2-1.pdf|title=The first of the major Barzani revolts|newspaper=historyofkurd.com|date=2016|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728074611/http://www.historyofkurd.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B2-1.pdf|archive-date=2017-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> One decade later in 1943 [[Mustafa Barzani]] was escape from his exile in [[Sulaymaniyah]], he returned to [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]] and he had visited a number of villages in the region and a number of village men soon joined him and captured and disarmed the local police. A bloody clash between the [[Mustafa Barzani|Barzani]] and [[Military intelligence]] officers in Pendro, this clash that led to the death of the three [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraqi]] Military intelligence officers, that was the beginning of [[1943 Barzani revolt]]. Occupation of Barzan on 7 October 1945 by [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]], forced [[Mustafa Barzani|Barzani]] to order his forces to retreat from the region and cross into [[Iranian Kurdistan]] with nearly three thousands Barzani, 165 of them came from Pendro. And later settled and join establishing the [[Republic of Mahabad]]. After [[Mahabad Republic]] was overrun by Iran's army, Barzani and his 500 followers took refuge in [[Soviet]], including 19 Pendroi.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barzani|first1=Massoud|title=Mustafa Barzani and the Kurdish Liberation Movement|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-29316-1|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yx7UqM31KYUC&pg=PA65|date=2003}}</ref> Over 150 Pendroi participated in [[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War|Aylul Revolution]] and Gulan Revolution. After [[1975 Algiers Agreement|Algiers Accord]] over sixty thousands Kurdish, including 116 Pendroy families forced to become refugees, fleeing mostly to neighbouring Iran. On 25 June 1978 Iraqi Army removed all villagers nearer the border to different camps in [[Erbil Province]] and destroyed the villages, all Pendroi settled in Bahirka camp, the region entirely destroyed and left uninhabitable.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHAT HAPPENED IN THE KURDISH GENOCIDE|url=http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&pnr=37|website=uk.gov.krd|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080615/http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&pnr=37|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> Genocide against the Barzani Kurds by Iraqi regime in 1983, the killing of the 8,000 Barzani, 16 victims were from Pendro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drmohammedihsan.com/Images/Service/FROM%20BLUEPRINT%20TO%20GENOCIDE.pdf|title=FROM BLUEPRINT TO GENOCIDE?|newspaper=drmohammedihsan.com|date=2014|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109061446/http://drmohammedihsan.com/Images/Service/FROM%20BLUEPRINT%20TO%20GENOCIDE.pdf|archive-date=2017-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Agency, krg.org |title=Iraqi tribunal rules Barzani killings in 1983 were genocide |url=https://ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2011/5/state5086.htm |website=ekurd.net |access-date=2018-09-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810143427/https://ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2011/5/state5086.htm |archive-date=2018-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Various waves of Kurdish genocide|url=http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&smap=170000&pnr=48|website=uk.gov.krd|access-date=2017-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901063048/http://uk.gov.krd/genocide/pages/page.aspx?lngnr=12&smap=170000&pnr=48|archive-date=2017-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[Kurdish rebellion of 1983|Kurdish Rebellion]] some Pendroi families went back to Pendro and rebuilt new village in the north, toward to the mount [[Mount Butin|Butin]] an area of the land called \"Mlane\", once again their village destroyed by Iraqi regime in 1987 and villagers forced to become refugees in Iran.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pendro Etymology|url=http://ekurds.com/kurdish/pendro.htm|work=ekurds|access-date=2017-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417155614/http://www.ekurds.com/kurdish/pendro.htm|archive-date=2017-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1991, after [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|Kurdish Uprisings]], people came back to the village and it was rebuilt in 1994 by one of the [[United Kingdom|British]] organizations. The new village rebuilt about {{convert|1.5|km|mi|0}} west of Pendro a region of the land called \"Chema\". But two years later the village destroyed during the [[Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict (1978\u2013present)|PKK-Turkish]] conflict.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nawzad Hluri |title=\u0632\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u0647\u200c\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u06c6\u0631\u062f\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0634\u0647\u200c\u0648\u06cc \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0648\u06cc \u0641\u0695\u06c6\u0643\u0647\u200c \u062a\u0648\u0631\u0643\u06cc\u06cc\u0647\u200c\u0643\u0627\u0646 |url=http://wishe.net/dreja.aspx?=hewal&jmare=22855&Jor=1 |work=wishe |access-date=2017-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810112121/http://wishe.net/dreja.aspx?=hewal&jmare=22855&Jor=1 |archive-date=2018-08-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:KurdistanMountainClimbing.jpg|Kurdistan Mountain Climbing Federation Heading to the Sardav Canyon (2015)|thumb|left]]\nPendro lies at an altitude of {{convert|1325|m|ft|0}} [[above mean sea level|above sea level]] and covers an area over {{convert|10.0|km2|sqmi|1}}. It is located in northern [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]]. The terrain mostly consists of mountains and [[hill]]s, with very little moderately sloping [[plain]]s. The lowest point is the '''Chema''' [[Stream]], at 1174 metres, and the highest is [[Mount Butin]], at 2,534 metres, in the Chema, just west of the confluence of the many [[Stream]]. Mountain ranges in the proximity of the village are [[Mount Butin|Butin]] and '''Kerye Spindare''', more to the south are '''Misek''' and '''Kore Hure'''. Pendro has neither rivers nor lakes. In terms of land boundaries, Pendro borders Edlbey, Zet, Banan, Shive, Dezo, Spindare, Navkorka, Binavye, Stope, Selke, Guiza Walati and [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]] for over {{convert|50|km|mi|0}}. The nearest major towns are '''Sherwan Mezin''', {{convert|14|km|mi|0}} away to the south-east, [[Barzan, Iraq|Barzan]], {{convert|18|km|mi|0}} away to the south and capital [[Erbil]], {{convert|172|km|mi|0}} to the south (by road). The village-wide common lands called: ''Sebaski'', ''Gure'', ''Chema'', ''Mlane'', ''[[Mount Butin|Butine]]'', ''Elye'', ''leri'' and ''Ser xingel''. Pendro has so many [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]]s the main springs are ''Kanya Gundi'', ''Kanya Serderave'', '' Kani Jefre'', ''Kanya Mlane'', ''Kanya Butine'', ''Kanya Helara'' and ''Kanya Mira''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Bordering villages ===\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Pendro\n|North     = '''Shive''', '''Banan'''\n|Northeast = [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Derek]]\n|East      = '''Edlbey''', '''Zet'''\n|Southeast = \n|South     = '''Guiza Walati''', '''Selke''', '''Stope'''\n|Southwest = \n|West      = '''Navkorka''', '''Binavye'''\n|Northwest = '''Spindare''', '''Dezo'''\n}}\n\n==Climate==\nPendro's clamate is [[Hot-summer humid continental climate|Hot/warm-summer humid continental]] (''[[humid continental climate|Dsa]]'') according to [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Weather in region is moderate especially in winter which is very cold and rainy (more than {{convert|1500|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} in some years) in addition to the fall of {{convert|150|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} of snow annually. January is the wettest month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weather in Pendro, Arbil|url=https://us.worldweatheronline.com/pendro-weather/arbil/iq.aspx|website=us.worldweatheronline.com}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box |metric first= Yes |single line= Yes |location= Pendro (2009\u20132016)\n|Jan record high C= 13.0\n|Feb record high C= 17.0\n|Mar record high C= 20.0\n|Apr record high C= 27.0\n|May record high C= 33.0\n|Jun record high C= 39.0\n|Jul record high C= 44.0\n|Aug record high C= 44.0\n|Sep record high C= 40.0\n|Oct record high C= 31.0\n|Nov record high C= 22.0\n|Dec record high C= 14.0\n|Jan high C= 9.5\n|Feb high C= 12.2\n|Mar high C= 16.2\n|Apr high C= 23.0\n|May high C= 29.6\n|Jun high C= 36.7\n|Jul high C= 41.0\n|Aug high C= 40.7\n|Sep high C= 35.2\n|Oct high C= 27.5\n|Nov high C= 18.8\n|Dec high C= 12.2\n|Jan mean C = 6.1\n|Feb mean C = 8.5\n|Mar mean C = 11.7\n|Apr mean C = 18.0\n|May mean C = 25.6\n|Jun mean C = 31.7\n|Jul mean C = 35.3\n|Aug mean C = 34.7\n|Sep mean C = 29.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.3\n|Nov mean C = 14.6\n|Dec mean C = 7.1\n|Jan low C= 1.8\n|Feb low C= 3.2\n|Mar low C= 